Three places to write the type explicitly.

Even though inference usually succeeds, there are three places where you should write the type by hand.

The first is on public method signatures. A method's parameter and return types are its contract with the rest of the codebase. If you let the return type be inferred, a downstream change to the body can silently change the type that callers depend on. Always annotate the return type of a method other code calls.

The second is when inference would pick something wider than you intended. A classic example is a list that mixes an integer, a decimal, and a string. The compiler infers a wide common type that is almost never what you wanted. Writing the type explicitly makes the intent visible — or, better, restructure the code so the list is not heterogeneous in the first place.

The third is when the right-hand side is recursive, or mutually recursive. A recursive method needs a declared return type to break the inference cycle. Take a factorial defined in terms of itself — without the return type annotation, the compiler cannot infer it and reports that a recursive method needs a result type.

So the pattern is: lean on inference for local values, and be deliberate at public signatures, heterogeneous collections, and recursion.
